To use visual studio code, you must tailor your environment.

INSTALL:
--------
1. Install Visual Studio Code (https://code.visualstudio.com/download)

2. Install Cygwin (https://www.cygwin.com)
   - Be sure to install the Develop category.  This installs git plus gcc.

CLONE:
------
1. In a cygwin window, clone the robot dev project


CONFIGURE:
----------

1. Open the folder containing the newarch project

2. Update the Debug Configuration
   a. Select Debug/Open Configurations from the menu
   b. Find thr eentry that says miDebuggerPath and change the path to match
      your installation of cygwin (most will say C:\\cygwin64\\bin\\gdb.exe)
   c. Save the file

3. Update the your terminal settings to use cygwin
   a. Select File/Preferences/Settings
   b. Copy the following into the User Settings window on the right
      {
          // start bash, not the mintty, or you'll get a new window
          "terminal.integrated.shell.windows": "D:\\cygwin\\bin\\bash.exe",
          // Use this to keep bash from doing a 'cd ${HOME}'
          "terminal.integrated.env.windows": {
              "CHERE_INVOKING": "1"
          },
          // Make it a login shell
          "terminal.integrated.shellArgs.windows": [
              "-l"
          ],
      }
   c. Save the settings file


Now Visual Studio code is setup to work fairly well with gradle, cygwin, and gcc.

